  <!-- SECTION 1: WHAT IS -->
  <div class="sec-mark" id="what-is">DEFINITION</div>
  <div class="prose">
    <h2>What is Shopify Server-Side Tracking?</h2>
    <p>Server-side tracking (also called Conversions API, server-to-server tracking, or S2S tracking) sends conversion events directly from your web server to advertising platforms &mdash; completely bypassing the customer&rsquo;s browser. Instead of relying on a JavaScript pixel in the browser to fire when a purchase completes, a webhook fires from Shopify&rsquo;s backend the moment payment is confirmed, routing event data directly to Meta&rsquo;s Conversions API, Google&rsquo;s Enhanced Conversions endpoint, and TikTok&rsquo;s Events API.</p>
    <p>The key distinction is where the event originates. A browser pixel depends on the customer&rsquo;s device: their browser settings, installed extensions, network conditions, and whether they accepted your cookie banner. A server event originates from Shopify&rsquo;s infrastructure &mdash; it fires regardless of what the customer&rsquo;s browser does, making it immune to ad blockers, iOS privacy restrictions, and Safari&rsquo;s Intelligent Tracking Prevention.</p>
    <h3>Server-side vs browser pixel: the architecture</h3>
  </div>
  <div class="flow-compare">
    <div class="flow-card broken">
      <div class="flow-title">&#x2715; Browser pixel only</div>
      <div class="flow-steps">
        <div class="flow-step blocked"><span class="flow-step-n">1</span>Customer completes purchase</div>
        <div class="flow-step blocked"><span class="flow-step-n">2</span>Thank-you page loads in browser</div>
        <div class="flow-step blocked"><span class="flow-step-n">3</span>Pixel JavaScript tries to fire</div>
        <div class="flow-step blocked"><span class="flow-step-n">4</span>Ad blocker / ITP / ATT blocks it</div>
        <div class="flow-step blocked"><span class="flow-step-n">5</span>Conversion never recorded</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-card fixed">
      <div class="flow-title">&#x2713; Server-side tracking</div>
      <div class="flow-steps">
        <div class="flow-step ok"><span class="flow-step-n">1</span>Customer completes purchase</div>
        <div class="flow-step ok"><span class="flow-step-n">2</span>Shopify backend fires webhook instantly</div>
        <div class="flow-step ok"><span class="flow-step-n">3</span>Make.com receives full order payload</div>
        <div class="flow-step ok"><span class="flow-step-n">4</span>HTTP module POSTs to Meta/Google/TikTok</div>
        <div class="flow-step ok"><span class="flow-step-n">5</span>Conversion recorded every time</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>Server-side tracking does not replace your browser pixel &mdash; it runs in parallel with it. The pixel handles upper-funnel events (ViewContent, AddToCart, InitiateCheckout) that server webhooks cannot capture since they only fire on confirmed payment. Together, the two methods give each ad platform the most complete signal possible.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- SECTION 2: WHY 2026 -->
  <div class="sec-mark" id="why-2026">WHY IT MATTERS IN 2026</div>
  <div class="prose">
    <h2>Why Server-Side Tracking Is Non-Negotiable in 2026</h2>
    <p>The browser tracking environment has degraded dramatically since 2021 and continues to worsen. iOS 14.5 introduced App Tracking Transparency (ATT), requiring explicit opt-in for cross-app tracking &mdash; approximately 62% of iOS users decline. iOS 17 added Link Tracking Protection, which strips UTM and click-ID parameters from URLs in Safari Private Browsing and Mail. Safari&rsquo;s Intelligent Tracking Prevention deletes first-party cookies after 7 days and blocks all third-party cookies. Firefox Enhanced Tracking Protection blocks third-party cookies by default. Chrome&rsquo;s Privacy Sandbox continues its phased rollout despite delays.</p>
    <p>The cumulative effect: on a typical Shopify store with normal UK or US traffic mix, 30&ndash;40% of actual purchases are invisible to your browser pixel. Your ad platforms are optimising delivery on incomplete data &mdash; which means higher CPAs, suppressed ROAS, and budget allocated to audiences that look unprofitable but aren&rsquo;t.</p>
    <h3>How much data are you actually losing?</h3>
  </div>
  <div class="data-loss-bar">
    <div class="dlb-title">Estimated browser pixel loss by platform (2026 UK/US traffic mix)</div>
    <div class="dlb-row"><span class="dlb-label">Meta</span><div class="dlb-track"><div class="dlb-fill meta"></div></div><span class="dlb-val meta">~35%</span></div>
    <div class="dlb-row"><span class="dlb-label">Google</span><div class="dlb-track"><div class="dlb-fill google"></div></div><span class="dlb-val google">~28%</span></div>
    <div class="dlb-row"><span class="dlb-label">TikTok</span><div class="dlb-track"><div class="dlb-fill tiktok"></div></div><span class="dlb-val tiktok">~22%</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="callout warn">
    <span class="callout-label">iOS 17/18 specific impact</span>
    <p>Safari&rsquo;s Link Tracking Protection in iOS 17+ strips <strong>fbclid</strong> and <strong>gclid</strong> parameters from URLs, breaking click-attribution for users who tap your ads in Safari. Server-side CAPI with hashed email matching is the only way to attribute these conversions. If your store has more than 40% iOS traffic, this alone justifies implementing CAPI.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>Server-side tracking does not recover every lost event &mdash; it recovers the events that were lost due to browser restrictions, not events from users who genuinely did not convert. The 20&ndash;40% recovery figure represents real purchases that happened but were invisible to your pixel.</p>
  </div>

